{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_oliver_ver01/data/sn83045462/0028060057A/1930102101/0378.xml":{"full_text":"A-4\nHEFLIN PLEA GOES\nTO ALABAMA KM.\nFellowship Forum to Issue\n250,000 Papers in Last-\nHour Campaign Drive.\nr BY FREDERIC WILLIAM WILE.\n..Calling upon \"the patriotic Protestant\nfcrces of America\" to prevent \"rum and\nRomanism\u201d from \u201ccrucifying Tom Hef\nlin on the papal cross,\" a great drive for\nthe Alabama \u201cJeffersonian Democrat's\"\nre-election to the Senate will feature\nthe final fortnight of the campaign.\nThe drive appears to have been or\nganized by the Fellowship Forum, which\nto commonly considered to speak for the\nKkKlux Klan.\n\u2022The current issue of the paper an\nnounces that a \u201cBig Heflin Special\u201d of\n390,000 copies Is to be sent into Alabama\n09 October 25. \u201cThis will be the vfery\nlast chance we will have,\u201d say% James\nS. Vance, editor and manager, of the\nFellowship Forum, \u201cto give Tom Heflin\nlift and the enemies of our country\na body blow.\u201d The first \u201cBig Heflin\nSpecial Edition\u201d of 125,000 copies was\ndistributed in Alabama earlier this\nmonth. For a contribution of $25,\nJ. 900 copies are sent.\n1 Believe Heflin\u2019s Doom Sealed.\nAccording to first-hand information\nreaching this writer from regular Dem\nocratic quarters In Alabama, Senator\nHeflin will need all the support he can\nget, if he Is to avoid defeat on Nv\u00bbws\nber 4. He Is conducting one of his typi\ncal whirlwind campaigns, speaking twice.,\na day and visiting every county In the\nState. Assured of the good show Heflin\nalways puts on, whether he Is on the\nstump or the floor of the Senate, big\ncrowds turn out whenever he appears.\nBut the Democratic forces behind John\nH. Bankhead, the party's regular sena\ntorial nominee, are convinced that Hef\nlin\u2019s doom is sealed. They are not\nclaiming victory by anything like a\nlandslide vote. If Bankhead can be\nelected by anything from 15,000 to\n30,000 majority, his managers will be\nsatisfied. They seem In no doubt that\nthis result can be accomplished. The\nstrong Democratic counties of the State,\nIt is foreshadowed, will pllt up a much\nheavier vote for Bankhead than they\ndid for Smith two years ago. Alabama\nwent Democratic for President In 1928\nby 7,000-odd. Heflin\u2019s s&atoriai ma\njority in 1924 was lIS.OOO/jvhen he ran\nagainst a Republican.\nAs recently as a month ago, the Heflin\ntide seemed to be running strong. His\nincessant onslaughts against \"the in\nfamous 27,\u201d his description of the Ala\nbama State committeemen who read\nhim out of the Democrats party, were\nynaklng an appeal. \u201cTom\u2019* Is effective\nwhen picturing himself as a martyr.\nHis argument that North. Carolina\nDemocrats had not attempted to punish\nSenator Simmons for \u2018disloyalty\u201d Was\nrammed home pretty tellingly, enabling\nHeflin to pose as the victim of personal\npersecution. The big voiced Senator\nhas also made some headway with an\nincreasing allusion to an occasion on\nwhich his opponent, Bankhead, once\npermitted a negro to sit on a Jury\nwhich was trying a white man in Ala\nbama.\n\"During the past two' or three weeks,\u201d\nwrites an Alabama Democrat of na\ntional renown, \u201cthere has been a sub\nstantial trend to the regular ticket\nheaded by Bankhead for Senator and\nMiller for governor. Heflin is very\nstrong in 15 or 20 counties among the\n\u2022hill-billies,\u2019 as we call them. These\nregions have always contained a very\nheavy Republican vote. The fathers\nof these voters were not in sympathy\nwith the Southern Confederacy and\nfurnished, as a result, twd keafcnents to\ntl* Federal Army during ihdjPlril War.\nIt is counties of \u2019that-\u2019\u2019 make-up that\nHeflin has his greatest strength.\nBankhead to Win by 2MM, Claim.\n\u201cThe Democratic State (Committee\nhas made the most 'effectiv#\"brganiza\ntlon In this campaign that Alabama\nhas ever known. It realized from un\nsatisfactory results In the 1928 presi\ndential campaign that a real fight and\na complete organization had to be made.\nI am convinced that the bulk of the\n67 counties of Alabama'\u2019are thoroughly\norganized now to the last township. In\nMiddle and South Alabama; where the\nold-time loyal Democratic vote has al\nways existed, there is odly A small mi\nnority that went off after Hoover two\nSrs ago, and most of these are corn\nback to the straight ticket this year.\nThe strong Democratic counties Will\npile up a much heavier vote for Bank\nhead and Miller than they gave Smith.\n\u201cReasonable authorities are assured\nthat Bankhead will beat Heflin by a\nminimum majority of 15,000 to 20,500.\nThere Is a probability that the majority\nmay run up to 40,000. A great many of\nthe Republican State and county lead\ners are opposed to HeftUf. They will\nnot vote for him because he has been\nso vituperative In his denunciations of\nthe Republican party all his life until\n1928. Many Republican leaders are\ntrying to get their partisans to vote for\ncounty tickets, where there are such,\nand not to vote for Heflin. The size\nof Bankhead s majority is going to de\npend upon the success of these anti-\nHefiln Republican leaders in carrying\nout their program.\u201d\n(Copyright. 1930.)\nKELLOGG SAYS NATIONS\nCAN GUARANTEE PEACE\nAmerican to Be Installed as Judge\nof World Court at The\nHague Thursday.\nBr the Associated Press.\nTHE HAGUE, October 21\u2014Frank\nB. Kellogg, former United States Sec\nretary of State, who will be Installed\nas a Judge of the World Court on\nThursday, vesterday In a statement told\nthe Associated Press that if the na\ntions of the world say \u201cwe want peace,\u201d\nthey will have It.\nIt goes without saying, Mr. Kellogg\ndeclared, that the world-wide business\ndepression has caused agitation. Os\nthis, he added, Germany provides a\ntypical example, but \u201cthere Is no cause\nfor undue anxiety.\u201d\nMr. Kellogg said he was very opti\nmistic atxrat efforts being made on all\naides for advancement of world peace.\n\"Fortunately,\u201d he continued, \u201cthe world\nprogresses and does not go backward.\nThe question Is simply whether the\npoliticians and the people wish to de\nvote themselves to peace.\"\nBROKERS\u2019 AID ASKED l\nStock Exchange Houses Get Plea\nto Contribute to Jobless Fund.\nNEW YORK. October 21 </P).\u2014An\nemergency employment committee or\nganized by bankers and industrialists\nto raise $150,000 weekly to provide\nwork for the jobless plans a special\ndrive for assistance from Stock Ex\nchange house.\nAccording to a plan now under dis\nciutlcn. every Stock Exchange hcuse\nwill be asked to contribute $3 a day\nfor at least one Individual during the\n4 Winter.\nCONVICTED OF FRAUD\nDENVER, October 21 UP).\u2014 Richard\nM. Crane, former president of the\ndefunct Association Industries Cor\nporat on, wra sentenced ,to from live\nto six years in pricon, and C T. Flynn,\nformer secretary of the firm, to four to\nfive years by District Judge James C.\nStarkweather yesterday.\nThey were convicted of conspiracy to\ndefraud In connection with .the failure\nOs the which the prosecution\nfill Rogers\nSays:\nBEVERLY HILLS. Calif.\u2014Every\nman has his own way of telling\nbad business is. The head\nwaiter at the big Del Monte\nt Hotel was tell\ning me of a big\nbanquet held\nthere the night\nbefore by a well\nknown organi\nzation, and he\nlamented, \u201cIt\nwasn\u2019t nothing\nlike the years\nbefore. Why, we\ncleaned up after\n\u2019em In less than\nan hour this\nmorning.\u201d That means times are so\nhard they are carrying their empty\nbottles home with \u2019em, but there was\na real barometer of business. Some\nking Is being crowned In Africa, and\nevery other king sent sympathy, and\neven presidents wired him that \u201cbe-\nIng the head man nowadays is over\nrated.\u201d\nNORRIS REQUESTS\nSTEBBINS PROBE\nWrites Nye Campaign Sum\nStatement Contradicts\nInquiry Evidence.\nBr the Associated Press.\nLINCOLN, Nebr., October 21.\u2014Sen\nator Oeorge W. Norris today requested\nSenator. Gerald P. Nye, chairman of the\nsenatorial campaign funds investigating\ncommittee, to return to Nebraska to\ninquire Into the statement by W. M.\nStebblns, State treasurer, that he do\nnated a SSOO bond to the campaign fund\nof Oeorge W. Norris, the Broken Bow\ngrocer, and that he gave $350 In cash to\na campaign to defeat the Nebraska\nSenator.\nStebblns was the Senator's principal\nopponent in his campaign for the Re\npublican senatorial nomination in the\nAugust primary. Norris won the nom\nination. Grocer Norris\u2019 filing as a can\ndidate for ttie nomination was ruled Il\nlegal by a State Supreme Court justice\nbecause of belated filing.\nThe request from Senator Norris de\nscribed the Stebblns statement as war\nranting farther inquiry \u201cin view of the\nsworn affidavit (campaign expense ac\ncount) of Mr. Stebblns purporting to\ngive a trpe and accurate account of his\nexpenditures in this campaign. This\nconfession of Mr. Stebblns is a flat con\ntradiction of this evidence already taken\nby yourself and Senator Dale.\n\u201cI sincerely hope that this investiga\ntion may take place before election, as\nlong before as possible, but If the work\nof the committee makes this Impossible,\nI respectfully request that such further\nInvestigation be made after election\nIt is a matter of such vast importance,\nparticularly to the Senate, that it seems\nto me that the matter cannot be ig\nnored and must be probed to the bot\ntom\u201d\nHULL AND BROCK APPROVED.\nSenate Probers Smile at Memphis\nVoting Testimony.\nBr the Associated Press.\nMEMPHIS. Tenn., October 21.\u2014The\nSenate Campaign Funds Committee\nannounced last night, at the conclusion\nof its public hearings in Tennessee, that\nit had found no basis for any charges\nserious enbugh to disqualify Cordell Hull\nor Senator w. S. Brock, victors In this\nState\u2019s Democratic senatorial primary.\nHull was nominated for the long term,\nand Senator Brock for the short term.\nChairman Gerald P. Nye and Senator\nRobert Wagner of the committee an\nnounced simultaneously that they found\n\u201cno substantial grounds for the more\nserious charges\u201d preferred in connection\nwith the conduct of the primary last\nAugust In Memphis and Shelby County.\nA hearing Into this county\u2019s primary\nended last night.\nNye Leaves tor Omaha.\nChairman Nye left last night for\nOmaha. Nebr. He said \u201cthere is a bare\npossibility\u201d that he may reopen hear\nings immediately into Nebraska\u2019s Re\npublican primary. After visiting\nNebraska he will visit Colorado.\nSenator Wagner said he would go\nimmediately to New York to take part\nin the Fall campaign there.\nSenator Nye, who says he holds the\nballot sacred, was told here yesterday\nhow they vote in some rural counties\nwhere a cigar box Is good enough to\nreceive any man's choice.\nThe Senate Campaign Funds Com\nmittee chairman alternately smiled and\nshowed amazement as James M. Cham\nberlain, chairman of the Democratic\nExecutive Committee and primary board\nIn Macon County, Tenn., testified that\nparty membership requirements and\npoll tax payments were waived in the\nAugust primary there.\n\"We never have required poll taxes\nup there,\u201d Chamberlain said. \u201cI\u2019ve\nbeen voting 17 years and never paid a\npoll tax and the old men tell me we\nnever have. We just don\u2019t do it.\u201d\nAs for party membership. Champer\nlain said he instructed election officers\nto waive It last time because \u201cwe heard\nup In Macon that in Alabama Demo\ncrats who voted for Hoover couldn\u2019t\nvote In the Democratic primary. Well,\nsir. nobody in our county w-ould vote\nfor A1 Smith as\u00bbd we knew a lot of good\nDemocrats would want to vote Demo\ncratic this time.\"\nSenator Nye asked what provision\nwps made to prevent ballots going\nastray.\nSwept Ballots Off Floor.\n\u201cWell? sir,\" said Chamberlain. \u201cI guess\nthere wasn\u2019t any. The ballots were\non the tables. I swept some up off the\nftoMr at my place the next day. But\nnobody would take any. Their hand\nwould be called if they were caught.\nsenator Wagner of New York asked 1\nhow election officers dis inguLshed be-\ntween Republicans and Democrats.\n\u201cWell,\u201d. Chamberlain said, \"you take\nIn my district, now. I know every man,\nwoman and child in It. There aren't\nmany of us and everybody knows every\nbody else.\u201d\nREPRESENTATIVE DYER\nURGES MODIFICATION\ni Declares Prohibition Enforcement\nFailure and Predicts Victory for\nParty Taking Wet Stand.\nBy the Associated Press,\nj ST. LOUIS, October 21.\u2014Declaring\nprohibition enforcement has failed, Rep\nresentative L. C. Dyer last night urged\nmodification of the Volstead act to per\nmit 2.75 per cent beer by weight, \u201cthus\nsatisfying 80 per cent of the people,\u201d\nwhom the Representative said are op\nposed to the present alcoholic definition\nof the law.\nDyer made his declaration at a din\nner of the Republican Professional and\nI Business Women\u2019s Clubs.\nHe predicted the people will make\nprohibition the \u201creal political Issue\u201d In\nthe next general ejection and that one\nor the other of the major parties \u201cwill\nhave the courage by that time to come\nI out against prohibition In Its present\nform.\u201d The party that does that, he\nsaid, \u201cwill win the election.\u201d\nSherman Whipple Diet.\nBROOKLINE, Mass., October 21 UP).\n\u2014Shcrmen Whipple, 68, widely known\ns lawyer, t'l-'d suddenly at his home here\ni yestcr morning after a brief attack\nfrf *\u2018*\u00ab*to\nTTTFI EVENING STAR, WASHINGTON, P. C., TUESDAY, OCTOBER 21, 1930.\nRITCHIE\u2019S ELECTION f\nSEEN IN MARYLAND\nRepublicans, However, Bat\ntle on With Hope of Up\nsetting Governor^\n(Continued From First Page.)\nbeen willing for him to step gracefully\nout of the picture, but they did not\nintend to have Albert C. Ritchie kicked\nout. In the twinkling of an eye the\nsituation changed.' The leaders who\nhad gone over to Mclntosh .'ound that\nthe rank and file and the ward leaders\nwould not follow them. Instead of\nnominating Mclntosh, In the end they\nall came trooping back to Ritchie, and\nMclntosh, who had declared his candi\ndacy for the nomination, withdrew in\nfavor of Ritchie.\nThe manner In which Gov. Ritchie\nhas benefited from the turn of circum\nstances is one of the amazing episodes\nof political history. He might have gone\nto the Senate of the United States in\n1926 If he had wished to do iso. He\ncould have had the nomination If he\nhad put out his hand for it. Instead,\nhowever, he decided to plug ahead as\nGovernor of Maryland, even though It\nmeant running in that year for -a third\nterm as chief executive of the State,\nand the nomination went to Senator\nTydings.\nRumblings Are Heard.\nUndeniably there is opposition on the\npart of a good many voters to Gov.\nRitchie\u2019s being elected for a fourth\nterm. Some of the Democrats feel that\nway about It themselves. There are the\nenemies he has made in his own party\nand there are men who feel that they\nshould have neen given a chance to run\nfor Governor, but have been held up by\nthe constantly recurring nomination of\nRitchie.\nOn the other hand. Gov. Ritchie has\na great personal following in the State.\nHis supporters insist that he has given\nMaryland an excellent administration.\nIf there was defalcation in the case of\nthe road funds, at least the Governor\ntook the matter in hand and cleaned up\nthe mess, they say, and they deny that\nthe road scandal can be made success\nfully an Issue today, although the Re\npublicans have sought to make It one.\nGov. Ritchie is as widely known for\nhis stand against the eighteenth amend\nment as he Is for his perennial holding\nof the governorship. The prohibition\namendment; to the Constitution had\nscarcely been proclaimed when the-Gov\nemor started demanding Its repeal. The\ndemands made' now by Oov. Roosevelt\nof New York, Dwight W Morrow. Re\npublican candidate for the Senate In\nNew Jersey, and A1 Smith, candidate\nfor President In 1928, all have followed\nlines laid down by Oov. Ritchie In the\npast.\nRons on Wet Ticket.\nRitchie has been the champion par\nexcellence of State rights when it came\nto deal with the liquor question. He\nIs a wet and as a wet he is running\nfor Governor of Maryland on a wet\nplatform and with a wet ticket.\nThis wet-and-dry issue Is the second,\nif not the first, issue In the guberna\ntorial campaign In Maryland this year.\nMayor Broenlng, who has been regard\ned as a wet In the past, is standing\non the Republican State platform,\nwhich demands strict adherence to the\nConstitution and the law.\nThe Republicans carried Maryland\ntwo years ago for a dry candidate for\nPresident. Mr. Hoover, against the wet\nA1 Smith. Indeed, Mr. Hoover\u2019s lead\nover Smith was surprisingly large In a\nState which i 6 reputed tp be -quite wet,\n78,000. With the Democrats taking Che\nwet side of the isau* again thte year,\nit is not to be wondered that the Re- 1\npublicans have sought to capitalize the\ndry sentiment In the State, which Is\nconsiderable outside of the City of Bal\ntimore.\nSo all the Republican candidates are\ndry* this year, even including Mayor\nBi ceiling, who is saying as little about\nthe subject as he can In his campaign.\nThere is one exception\u2014Col. John\nPhilip Hill, Republican nominee for the\nHouse in the third congressional dis\ntrict, located In Baltimore. Col. Hill\nIs the wettest of the wet. In a Demo\ncratic district he has been successfully\nelected several times to the House in\nthe past. He was leader -of the wet\ngroup In that body until he sought the\nRepublican nomination for the Senate\nfour years ago against former Senator\nWeller. He lost In the primary. Two\nyears ago Col. Hill sought to stage a\ncomeback and win his eld place in the\nHouse. He lost by exactly 330 votes to\nRepresentative Palmisano, a Democrat,\nwho had succeeded him In the House.\nOther Races in State.\nThe wet-and-dry Issue, therefore. Is\na dominating issue in the Maryland\ncampaign this year, except, It is true,\nIn the third congressional district,\nwhere the Republican and the Demo\ncrat are both wets.\nEven In the sixth district, where Rep\nresentative Fred Zihlman, Republican,\nand chairman of the House District\nCommittee, la seeking to succeed himself,\nthe wet and dry Issue has cropped out\nhard. Former Representative David J.\nLewis, Democrat, who while he was a\nmember of the House voted for the\neighteenth amendment and the Volstead\nact, is now out for light wines and beer,\ndeclaring that conditions under national\nprohibition are unbearable.\nSince the Civil War the Republicans\nhave elected Governors of Maryland ex\nactly twice. The first was in 1896, when\nLoyd Lowndes, Republican, defeated\nJohn J. Hurt 3, Democrat, and the occa\nsion was a revolt against the rule of\nthe late Senator Arthur Pue Gorman.\nThe second was in 1915, when Philip\nLee Ooldsborough, present Senator, de\nfeated Arthur Gorman, son of the late\nSenator, for the governorship. Oolds\nborough won by about 2,500 votes on\nthat occasion and there are Democrats\ni who say that enough Democratic ballots\ni were thrown out because they had been\nfaultily marked to have overcome that\nlead had those votes been counted.\nSee Ritchie Sure Winner.\nj In view of the political history of the\nState for the last 65 or 70 years, It does\nnot appear to be in the cards that\nRitchie will be defeated. Democratic\nleaders Insist that he will win the elec\ntion on November 4 by an even greater\nlead than he rolled up four years ago.\nThey are very confident.\nRepublicans, on the other hand, insist\nthat Broenlng, who three years ago de\nfeated his Democratic opponent for\nmayor of Baltimore, a ctrongly Demo\ncratic city, by 17,000, has a good chance\nto win. They are clinging to the hope\nthat enough Democrats who do not wish\nto see Ritchie receive a fourth term\nand enough dry Democrats out In the\nState will turn to their candidate to\nelect h m.\nThe registration Is quite large this\nyear, as compared to the registration In\nthe last \u201coff-year\u201d election In 1926. The\nDemocrats and the Republicans both\nare taking satisfaction from the large\nenrollment. The Democrats point to\nthe fact that the registration of Pemo\ncrats outnumbers by many thousands\nthe registration of Republicans. But\nthe Republicans take the view that a\nlarge enrollment In this off year means\nthat a great number of disgruntled\nDemocrats and drys are out to get Gov.\nRitchie\u2019s political scalp.\nTwo G. O. P. Members.\nThe Republicans have two Maryland\nRepresentatives in tip present House\nLtrwood L. Clark of the second district\nand Frederick N. Zihlman of the sixth\ndistrict. The second district has been\na Democratic district. It takes In a\npart of Baltimore, but includes a large\nterritory outside of the city. Clark,\nwho was defeated In 1926 in the race\nfor Representative of this district, won\nin 1928 by almost 10,000 votes over his\nDemocratic opponent.\nHe was swept Into office In the Hoo\nver and anti-Smith landslides, Clark is\na and he Is running eeasfwt'* wet.\nREMARKABLE PICTURES OF AIR CRASH\nI\n1\nP\nfJff\nML J\nMl\nv>\nA\nf\nm\nI\nM h 1\n1\nJr\nJr\nmB I\ni 99\nLeft: Plane of B. W. Mackie, a Long Island pilot, crashing to earth after It\nhad its toil clipped off in passing the plane of George Zinn of Philadelphia dur\ning the last event of the Eastern Air Races, at Trenton, N. J. Both pilots were\nkilled. The inset picture shows the two planes a moment after the collision.\nMackifs plane swerved from its course and headed directly for earth. Zlnn\u2019s\nplane continued for 150 feet, zoomed high in the air, then crashed, bursting into\n\u2014Wide World and Underwood Photco.\nWilliam P. Cole, Jr., who held the seat\nbefore Lin wood was elected and who\nwas defeated two years ago by the Re\npublican. The Republicans are count\ning on the dry issue to pull Linwood\nthrough In this contest. But the Demo\ncrats Insist that they will regain this\nseat.\nZihlman is having a real contest this\nyear in the sixth district. The dis\ntrict has been the Republican strong\nhold of the State in the past. Zihlman\nran far behind Hoover in the district\ntwo years ago. however, winning by\nonly 10,500 votes despite the Republi\ncan landslide. The Democrats are hop\ning to be able to hold down Broening's\nlead in this district to only a few thou\nsand votes and that they will be able\nto defeat Zihlman.\nLewis Patting Up Fight.\nLewis, the Democratic candidate,\nwhile a member of the House, fathered\nJhe postal savings bill which became\nlaw. Later he was appointed a mem\nber of the United States Tariff Com\nmission. It is far more of a fight in\nthat district this year than it has been\nin the past. Zihlman has been attacked\non several counts. Furthermore, there\nis seemingly a Democratic trend in\nMaryland at present and this may have\nits influence in the sixth as well as in\nother districts. Maryland has suffered\nfrom the drought and from business\ndepression.\nThe Republicans are still hopeful of\ncarrying the third district. Hill is\ncharging that Palmlsano was elected\ntwo years ago by fraudulent votes. In\ndeed, a House committee, after inves\ntigating the election on a contest\nbrought by Hill, found that some of the\nvotes cast for Palmlsano were fraudu\nlent, but the committee did not rec\nommend that Hill be seated and there\nthe matter stands now. Palmlsano is\npfcturing Hill as a resident of Wash\nington and not of Baltimore, because\nCol. Hill has law offices in the Na\ntional Capital and a house there as\nwell as in Baltimore.\nHURRICANE HITS MEXICO\nJ*\nMEXICO CITY, October 21 UP).\u2014\nDispatches from Vera Cruz today said\na hurricane, with winds ranging up\nto 100 miles an hour, struck that city\nyesterday, tylnw up traffic in the port.\nNo great damage was reported from\nthe wind, which was accompanied by\nheavy rainfall.\nDr. Durand and Wife Hurt.\nPALO ALTO, Calif., October 21 UP).\nt \u2014Dr. William P. Durand, Alternation\nally known mechanical engineer, and\ni his wife were Injured seriously here\nL yesterday when a heavy truck struck\ntheir automobile. Each suffered four\nF fractured ribs and possible Internal ln\nJ ur te\u00bb-\nT T>'W T T\nAre You Sick?\nAre You Discouraged?\nI Are You Financially\nDistressed?\nYOtJ NEED\nGOD-MAN\nA Devotional Manual for Daily\nt Use By BLAIR SCOTT\nIt reveals- to you the spiritual law of\nGod, under-which the Master met\nand overcame all beliefs of the flesh\nill and particularly those of SUPPLY\nTU AND HEALTH.\n(Pages 22. 22. 2\u00ab>\nFor Bible References, recording God\u2019s\navailable SPIRITUAL SUPPLY, UN\nLIMITED SUPPLY AND CON\ni TINUED SUPPLY:\n'Pane* Jll-1311\nFor Bible References, bestowing Christ\u2019s\nHEALING POWER ON ALL WHO\nBELIEVE.\n(Paott ill-113)\nj Whatever your problem\u2014\nt THIS BOOK\nBy the Osandson of Walter Scott\nI Unveils your God-given heritage of\nDominion\nLimp Cloth, $1.50\nAsk for it et the Auditorium\n1 Disciples Convention, Oct. 14-23\nORDER BLANK\nl Send to Your Bookseller or\nFLEMING H. REVELL CO.,\ntun Fifth Arena*. New York.\nPlease send me. postpaid- cop\nGOO and MAN, by Blair Bcott.\ni. Name\n4\nAddress\nenclosed\nI. LL\nPINCHOT CLAIMS\nHOOVER BACKING\nTells Radio Audience Presi\ndent Favors G. 0. P. Ticket\nin Pennsylvania.\nBy the Associated Brest.\nWASHINGTON, Pa, October 21.\nPresident Hoover stands for the elec\ntion of the entire Republics]) ticket in\nPennsylvania in the November 4 elec,\ntlon, Gifford Pinchot, Republican guber#\nnatorial candidate, declared in a radio\naddress her* today.\nCURTIS OPPOSES PINCHOT.\nPhiladelphia Publisher Announces\nBreak With Nominee.\nPHILADELPHIA, October 21 (/P).\u2014An\nother break In party lines In Pennsyl\nvania\u2019s gubernatorial campaign de\nveloped last night with the declaration\nof Cyrus H. K. Curtis, Philadelphia\npublisher, that he would not vote for\nGifford Pinchot, Republican nominee.\nMr. Curtis made his declaration at\na dinner given by Samuel M. Vauclaln,\nchairman of the board of the Baldwin\nLocomotive Works, and B. Dawson Cole\nman, vice chairman of the Association\nAgainst the Prohibition Amendment, to\nprominent industrial and business lead\ners of Pennsylvania.\n\"My objection to Mr. Pinchot,\u201d Mr.\nCurtis said, \u201cIs that he has always been\na trouble maker. He created trouble\nbetween President Roosevelt and Presi\ndent Taft. He created trouble in 1926\nwhen he Issued a certificate of doubt\nto William S. Vare.\u201d\nf 'f\ni\u00bb M\nClf\u00ab\u00a3 fjKmJfdJU&-\nOs course, if your Fall and Winter suits and\ngowns are originals or reproductions from\nChanel, Agnes, Patou or the foremost coutu\nriers of Paris you naturally must have shoes to\nmatch. Be consistent! The Stetson foreign staff\nhas sent us every smart model that is authentic\nstyle for daytime wear our own designers\nhave interpreted and refined them now,\nfor you, a foot from Paris, on a suave, gracious\nAmerican last. Models for bottomless purses\noffered at prices pleasing to those who keep\nSTYLE 2055\nThe latest Pari\nsian version of\nthe vogue for\nsuede black\nor brown, trim\nmed with\nbrown kid or\npatent leather\nor ms\nBrown\nSuede\nTHE\nof Washington f\nOwned and operated by The Stetson Shoe Co., Ins.\n1311 F Street i Washington, D. C\nGERMANY\u2019S ORATOR\nREACHES CAPITAL\nRemaining Youthful Contest\nFinalists to Gather at\nStar Tomorrow.\n\u00a3eins Bockhacker, Germany\u2019s entrant\nIn the Fifth International Oratorical\nContest, reached Washington at 1\no\u2019clock this afternoon, bringing the to\ntal number of world championship con\ntenders in the Capital to five.\nThe remaining three international\nfinalists for Saturday night\u2019s contest\nwere scheduled to reach Washington\nlater today. Javier Vlvanco R., Mex\nico\u2019s spokesman, who has been visiting\nin New York, and Clemente Peres-Za\nnartu of Chile, spokesman for South\nAmerica, were expected at Union Sta\ntion late this afternoon, while Paul Le\nduc. entrant from Canada, is expected\nin Washington late tonight.\nFollowing his arrival under the of\nficial auspices of the German govern\nment, voung Bockhacker went to the\nLee House, where he win stay while in\nWashington.\nWill Gather in Star Building.\nThe first gathering of all of the con\ntestants will take place at contest head\nquarters in The Star Building tomorrow\nat noon in preparation for the visit to\nthe White House. President Hoover will\ngreet the orators at 12:30 o\u2019clock and\npose with them for the official photo\ngraph.\nFrom the White House the party will\ngo to Western High School to be guests\nat a luncheon in their honor. Edmund\nGull ion. Western High School boy, who\nis the United States\u2019 spokesman in the\ncontest, will be host to his fellow con\ntenders for the championship. While\nat Western the boys will be photo\ngraphed in motion pictures by William\nP. Kennedy of The Star news staff.\nCopies of the film will be presented to\neach of the orators as a souvenir of\nhis participation In the contest here.\nDr. Marvin to Speak.\nDr. Cloyd Heck Marvin, president of\nGeorge Washington University, will be\nthe speaker at a luncheon which the\nCanadian Club is giving Thursday\nafternoon. At that function Paul Le\nduc, Canada\u2019s champion, will be the\nguest cf honor.\nWith two Army officers already an\nnounced as official timekeepers for the\nfinals, the Navy also will be represented\non this staff. Rear Admiral T. J. Cowie,\nU. 8. N\u201e retired, has been assigned to\nthis duty by the Navy Department. The\ntiming board now includes Rear Ad\nmiral Cowie, Maj. Gen. Harry L. Gil\nchrist, chief of Chemical Warfare Serv\nice, U. S. A., and Maj. Gen. Amos A.\nFries, U. 8. A., retired.\nThe contest will be held In Consti\ntution Hall at 8 o\u2019clock Saturday night.\nSENATOR HAWES\nASSAILS DRY LAW\nBlamei Prohibition for Official Cor\nruption, Crime and Disre\ngard for Order.\nBy tbs Associated Press.\nST. LOUIS, October 21.\u2014Senator\nHarry B. Hawes, who delivered two\nspeeches in St. Louis last night, assailed\nprohibition, declaring it to be productive\nof official corruption, a huge increase in\ncrime and a general disregard for law\nand order.\nThe speeches were the first of a series\nHawes will make in St. Louis and other\nparts of the State in behalf of State\nand local Democratic tickets.\nThe country is suffering from the ills\nof prohibition, Hawes said, \"because an\nimpatient group of meddlesome people,\nimpatient with local government and\nlocal control, sought through an amend\nment to the Constitution to force their\nown opinion through the law over large\nsections of our country and millions of\npeople who are opposed to prohibition.\n\u201cWe were promised that the Volstead\nlaw would fill our churches with wor\nshipers, empty *our jails and asylums;\nthat crime would decrease, health would\nImprove and there would be general\nhappiness and contentment. None of\nthese things has happened; none of\nthese promises has been fulfilled; quite\nthe contrary. There has been no in\ncrease in church attendance, the num\nber of insane has Increased and prisons\nare filled to overflowing.\n\u201cPresident Hoover has called this a\n\u2018noble experiment,\u2019 a phrase which\npleased both wets and drys. To be\nnoble a thing must be good, it must be\nhonorable, it must achieve something,\nand we know that the Volstead act has\nnot done this. So it leaves the emphasis\nupon the word \u2018experiment\u2019 and the ex\nperiment has proved a failure.\u2019\u2019\nOratory Officials\nMi\ni\ni\ni\ni\n\n\n\n\n1\ni-\nJ(\n1\nMi i\nmk\nfcr V-js. .v.^al\nUpper: Rear Admiral T. J. Cowie,\nU. S. N., who hu joined the time\nkeepers\u2019 staff tor Saturday night\u2019s finals.\nLower: Dr. Richard Henry Wilson,\nhead of the romance language depart\nment at the University of Virginia,\nwhose photograph was inadvertantly\nomitted from the group of Judges who\nwere announced last Saturday.\nCHALLENGE 15,000 VOTES\ni Republicans and Democrats File\nBulky Affidavits in Kansas City.\nKANSAS CITY, October 21 (JP).\nQualifications and the rights of more\nthan 15,000 persons to vote in the gen\neral election November 4 were chal\nlenged in affidavits filed with the Elec\ntion Board yesterday.\nMore than 10,000 affidavits were of\nsered by Republicans and 2,500 to 2,000\nby Democratic organizations.\nRepublican leaders charge that 200\nDemocrats on city and county pay rolls\nhave registered in various precincts\ntwo, three, four and even five times.\nCOME ON FOLKS!\nWe're All Set\nWhere Old Friends or Our\nMeet\nby *Seventk Annual\nTT\njf Harvest\nif/.ii folk*\u2019 4\n7th annual tj\ntforour H m rlome a.-\nFestival -i\nlooh .p tt m \u2014where we have gath-\nCornstalk r ered a crop of Men\u2019*\nbins, atl< j Smart Modem Mer-\nSTn j\u00a3 9 a chandise in good old* r\ngood c^ee ren tvf fashioned values t\ntim* u>hen Never in years has\nJl your dollar hid tho\n'\"\u201cvZ'r To Overcoats\nBui,., AI n.\n\"Mp., B and (Specially Priced)\n*av. u,\nvest ft \u2018tar-\nNit,' F, \u2018tivat\n0ft.,,.\naid re 7:30\nWhen you see these\n*OhMo \u201cstand-out\" values\nyou\u2019ll think it's back\nbefore the war!\n400 Tempting Topcoats, 19\u2019 75\n200 Silk-Lined Tuxedos, 32 ,5\n$3.50 Bond Street Spats .$2.45\n$2.50 Outseam Cape Gloves $1.95\n$2.50 Madras Broadcloth\nPajamas $1.95\n$2.50 Beaverbrook End End\nMadras Shirts $1.65\n$1.25 Famous Kut-Ful Knee\nUnion Suits 85c\nSI.OO Wool and Silk Wool Hose, 69c\n(3 prs., $2)\n75c Fancy Silk Hose .55c\n35c Fancy Bordered Handkfs. .5 for $1\nHOME OF SMITH SMART SHOES\nMIXED-UP POLITICS\nFEATURE CAMPAIGN\nRepublicans and Drys Back\nDemocrats and Wets, and\nVice Versa.\nBy the Associated Press.\nPolitical cross currants are forcing a\npatchwork design in the 1910 congres\nsional campaign, with both parties In\nvolved In the occasional mfir-ups.\nIn scattered contests over the Nation\nDemocrats are supporting Republicans,\nRepublicans campaigning for Demo\ncrats, wets supporting drys In some In\nstances, and drys espousing campaigns\nof wets.\nIn Pennsylvania, some Republican\nleaders have announced opposition to\nthe Republican gubernatorial nominee;\nClifford Pinchot, while some dry Demo\ncratic chieftains have deserted their\nwet candidate, John Hemphill.\nLa Follette Speaks for Democrats.\nSenator La Follette, Republican, of\nWisconsin, is preparing to taka the\nstump In behalf of two Demoreatto\ncandidates. Senator Thomas J. Walsh\nIn Montana, and Id ward P. Ooattgaa\nIn Colorado.\nReports of party switches come from\nthe heated Nebraska senatorial net,\nwhere Senator Georgs W. Norris, Re\npublican opponent of the Hoover ad\nministration, is fighting Gilbert N,\nHitchcock, Democratic nominee. Mr.\nHitchcock received assurance of support\nfrom the Democratic Senatorial Com\nmittee after he had demanded an ex\nplanation of a published report that\nthe committee was pursuing a \u2018\u2018hands\noff\u201d policy in his campaign.\nDown in Alabama, the Republicans\nrefrained from putting up a senatorial\ncandidate In the race between Benator\nHeflin and John H. Bankhead, the\nDemocratic nominee. Heflin was forced\nfrom the Democratic ticket for his fail\nure to support the presidential candle.'\ndacy of Alfred K. Smith In 1928.\nPeso, Dry, Supports Wets.\nSenator Fees of Ohio, the chairman\nof the Republican National Committed\nand an advocate of natloftal prohibi\ntion, Is working as hard for the Repub\nlican senatorial candidates In SthteS*'\nwhere they happen to be wet as lor\nthose in States where their platform\nis dry. Senator Tydlngs of Maryland,\nthe chairman of the Democratic Sena\ntorial Campaign Committee, Is an un\nrelenting foe of national prohibition,\nbut he Is giving as much attention to--\nthe campaign of dry Democratic noml-\nnees as of the wets.\nLovette to Oppose Reece.\nGREENEVILLE. Tenn., October *1\nOP).\u2014O. B. Lovette announced yester\nday that he will oppose Representative\nCarroll Reece In the first district con\ngressional race November 4, running as\nan Independent Republican against\nReece, the Republican nominee.","height":"25323","width":"19773"}}
